RESIDENTS got the shock of their lives when a 47-year-old man killed himself on Tuesday afternoon by climbing on to an electrical transformer. The man, believed to be Mozambican, apparently cut the power line with a broken bottle and was electrocuted on the spot.He was in Kabokweni, outside White River in Mpumalanga, to look for his brother who recently moved to South Africa. if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>It’s believed before he reached Gutshwa Village, where he killed himself, he was robbed of his possessions and was stranded. Witnesses said he was frustrated that no one could help him find his brother. Kabokweni cops were then called to the scene. Police spokeswoman Captain Shirley Ngomane said: “On arrival, we tried to talk him down but he refused. “He cut the cables and brought them together and was electrocuted. “We’ve opened an inquest docket and are investigating the matter.”Eskom spokesman Eric Khoza said: “We sympathise with the family. But we’re pleading with the community not to come into contact with electrical infrastructure.”